We have divisors $\Cal D,\Cal D_i,\Cal D_{ij}\subset C^5\setminus\bigcup\limits_{i<j}\Delta_{ij}$ that
parametrize configurations of  marked points $p_1,\ldots,p_5\in C$ satisfying any of the following equivalent conditions:
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\delta\in E$ or $\delta_i\in E_i$ or $\delta_{ij}\in E_{ij}$, respectively.
\item $\delta\in R$ or $\delta_i\in R$ or $\delta_{ij}\in R$, respectively.
\item $\delta-K$ or $P-K-2p_i$ or $P-2p_i-2p_j$, respectively, is an effective divisor.
\end{enumerate}
Divisors $\Cal D,\Cal D_i,\Cal D_{ij}$ can also be characterized using geometric conditions:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[($\Cal D$)]  the unique quadric surface in $\Bbb P^3$ containing $C$ is singular.
\item[($\Cal D_i$)] the tangent line at $p_i$ to $C\subset \Bbb P^3$ intersects $C$ at another point.
\item[($\Cal D_{ij})$] tangent lines at $p_i$ and $p_j$ intersect.
\end{enumerate}

